# Data exported from: https://www.fec.gov/data/advanced/?tab=bulk-data
# Read in data
raw = spark.read.format('csv')\
    .option('header', 'false')\
    .option('delimiter', '|')\
    .load('2_contributions/*.txt')
    
# Rename columns
old_cols = raw.columns
new_cols = ['candidate_id', 'candidate_name', 'incumbent_challenger_status', 'party_code',
            'party_affiliation', 'receipts', 'transfers_from_auth_comm', 'disbursements',
            'transfers_to_auth_comm', 'beginning_cash', 'ending_cash', 'contrib_from_candidate',
            'loan_from_candidate', 'other_loans', 'candiate_loan_repayment', 'other_loan_repayment',
            'debts_owed_by', 'tot_indiv_contrib', 'candidate_state', 'candidate_district',
            'special_election_status', 'primary_election_status', 'runoff_election_status',
            'general_election_status', 'general_election_percentage', 'contrib_from_other_pol_comm',
            'contrib_from_party_comm', 'coverage_end_date', 'refunds_to_indiv', 'refunds_to_comms']

col_dict = dict(zip(old_cols, new_cols))

for each in old_cols:
    raw = raw.withColumnRenamed(each, col_dict[each])
    
# Drop columns not included in current year's data
raw = raw.drop('special_election_status', 'primary_election_status',\
               'runoff_election_status', 'general_election_status', 'general_election_percentage',\
               'beginning_cash', 'ending_cash', 'contrib_from_candidate',\
               'loan_from_candidate', 'other_loans', 'candiate_loan_repayment', 'other_loan_repayment',\
               'contrib_from_other_pol_comm', 'contrib_from_party_comm', 'coverage_end_date',\
               'refunds_to_indiv', 'refunds_to_comms')

# Create new column with last name only to join with vote count data
raw = raw.withColumn('candidate', split('candidate_name', ', ').getItem(0))

# Data exported from https://transition.fec.gov/general/FederalElections2016.shtml
# Read in data
votes = spark.read.format('csv')\
    .option('header', 'true')\
    .load('1_votes/*.csv')

# Create new column to join with financial data
votes = votes.withColumn('candidate', upper(col('candidate_last')))

# Change state for presidents
votes = votes.withColumn('state',
                when(votes['state'] == 'NA', '00').otherwise(votes['state']))\
            .withColumn('candidate', ltrim(votes['candidate']))\
            .withColumn('win_indicator', rtrim(votes['win_indicator']))

votes = votes.withColumn('candidate', rtrim(votes['candidate']))\
            .withColumn('win_indicator', ltrim(votes['win_indicator']))
            
# Join financial data with vote counts and select only columns for modeling
df = raw.join(votes, (raw.candidate == votes.candidate) & (raw.candidate_state == votes.state)) \
    .select('candidate_id', 'candidate_name', 'incumbent_challenger_status', 'party_code',
            'party_affiliation', 'receipts', 'disbursements', raw.candidate_state,
            'general_vote_count', 'general_vote_percentage', 'win_indicator', 'body', raw.candidate, 'year', 'transfers_from_auth_comm', 'transfers_to_auth_comm')
           
df = df.withColumn('dupe_funds',
                  when((df['transfers_from_auth_comm'] != '0') & (df['transfers_from_auth_comm'] != '0'), 'dupe').otherwise('ok'))

df = df.withColumn('total_receipts',
                  when((df['dupe_funds'] == 'ok'), df['receipts']).otherwise(df['receipts']-df['transfers_from_auth_comm']))\
        .withColumn('total_disbursements',
                  when((df['dupe_funds'] == 'ok'), df['disbursements']).otherwise(df['disbursements']-df['transfers_to_auth_comm']))

df = df.withColumn('party_affiliation',
                  when((df['party_affiliation'] != 'DEM') & (df['party_affiliation'] != 'REP'), 'Other').otherwise(df['party_affiliation']))\
        .withColumn('win_indicator',
                  when((df['win_indicator'] == 'W'), 1).otherwise(0))\
        .withColumn('receipts_per_vote',
                  df['total_receipts'] / df['general_vote_count'])\
        .withColumn('net_receipts',
                  df['total_receipts'] - df['total_disbursements'])
    
df = df.fillna({'party_affiliation': 'X', 
                'total_receipts': 0,
               'total_disbursements': 0,
               'general_vote_count': 0,
               'general_vote_percentage': 0,
               'incumbent_challenger_status': 'X'})

Money in Politics¶

Presidential candidates are now spending hundreds of millions of dollars to run for office. While some of these funds come from individual donors, much of it comes from corporations and special interest group. But does all this money really work? Is the effect so strong that winners and losers can be predicted based on the amount of money raise?

The Federal Election Commission (FEC) tracks campaign contributions for all candidates. A candidate is defined as an individual seeking office who receives contributions or spends more than $5,000. A candidate may form his/her own committee in addition to authorizing other committees to raise money on their behalf. The FEC provides a data set with all contributions from authorized committees aggregated for each candidate. Separately, the FEC also makes available total vote counts for all candidates following the electino.

For this analysis, data has been combined for the 2011-2012 and the 2015-2016 election cycles. The contribution data set was joined with vote totals for both election cycles. The final data set used included for 3,542 candidates:

  • name
  • party affiliation
  • incumbent/challenger/open seat status
  • office sought (senate, house, president)
  • total contributions
  • total disbursement
  • win/loss indicator

For the predictive models, party, incumbency, office sought, contributions and disbursements will be used to predict a candidates win/loss.

from io import BytesIO
import base64

def plotdesc_figRight(fig, text, iwidth=None):
    bio = BytesIO()
    # save fig as png to bytes IO instead to disk
    fig.savefig(bio, format='png')
    plt.close(fig)
    iwidth = ' width={0} '.format(iwidth) if iwidth is not None else ''
    img_tag = "<img src='data:image/png;base64," + base64.b64encode(bio.getvalue()).decode('utf-8') + "'{0}/>".format(iwidth)
    datatable = '<table style="font-size:125%"><tr><td style="text-align: left;">{0}</td><td>{1}</td></tr></table>'.format(text, img_tag)
    display(HTML(datatable))
    
def plotdesc_figLeft(fig, text, iwidth=None):
    bio = BytesIO()
    # save fig as png to bytes IO instead to disk
    fig.savefig(bio, format='png')
    plt.close(fig)
    iwidth = ' width={0} '.format(iwidth) if iwidth is not None else ''
    img_tag = "<img src='data:image/png;base64," + base64.b64encode(bio.getvalue()).decode('utf-8') + "'{0}/>".format(iwidth)
    datatable = '<table style="font-size:125%" ><tr><td >{0}</td><td style="text-align: left;">{1}</td></tr></table>'.format(img_tag, text)
    display(HTML(datatable))

def ecdf(data):
    """Compute ECDF for a one-dimensional array of measurements."""
    n = len(data)
    x = np.sort(data)
    y = np.arange(1, n+1) / n
    return x, y

In [7]:
def get_confusionMatrix(df):
    """Returns the confusion matrix, true positive rate, and false negative rate"""
    
    df.createOrReplaceTempView("temp")

    actual_predicted_df = spark.sql(
    """SELECT 
        win_indicator as Actual, 
        prediction as Predicted 
    FROM temp""")


    actual_predicted_pd = actual_predicted_df.toPandas()
    actual_predicted_pd['Predicted'] = np.where(actual_predicted_pd.eval('Predicted == 0'), 'Loser', 'Winner')
    actual_predicted_pd['Actual'] = np.where(actual_predicted_pd.eval('Actual == 0'), 'Loser', 'Winner')

    results = pd.crosstab(actual_predicted_pd.Actual, actual_predicted_pd.Predicted)
    
    true_pos = results['Winner']['Winner']/(results['Loser']['Winner']+results['Winner']['Winner'])
    false_neg = results['Winner']['Loser']/(results['Loser']['Loser']+results['Winner']['Loser'])

    
    return results, true_pos, false_neg

Logistic Regression¶

The initial model for classifying winners and losers was logistic regression. The features used were:

  • categorical: incumbent status, party affiliation, body
  • continuous: total campaign contributions, net contributions

Categorical features were indexed and used to create dummy variables. Further, given the range of values for contributions, continuous features were scaled to a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one.

Grid search was combined with five fold cross validation to find optimal values for the elastic net parmater and regParam. The pipeline's evaluator used area under ROC to pick the best mode.

In [9]:
train, test = model_df.randomSplit([0.70, 0.3])

# Convert categorical columns to numeric and create dummy variables
categorical_columns = ['incumbent_challenger_status', 'party_affiliation', 'body']
indexers = [
    StringIndexer(inputCol=c, outputCol='{0}_indexed'.format(c))
    for c in categorical_columns
]

encoders = [OneHotEncoder(dropLast=True, inputCol=indexer.getOutputCol(),
                        outputCol='{0}_encoded'.format(indexer.getOutputCol()))
            for indexer in indexers
]

scaled_features = ['total_receipts', 'net_receipts']
s_va = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=scaled_features,
    outputCol='unscaled_features')

scalers = StandardScaler(withMean=True, withStd=True,
                         inputCol='unscaled_features', outputCol='scaled_features')

va = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=[encoder.getOutputCol() for encoder in encoders]+['scaled_features'],
    outputCol='all_features')

rForm = RFormula()

lr_0 = LogisticRegression().setLabelCol('win_indicator').setFeaturesCol('all_features')

stages = indexers+encoders+[s_va, scalers, va, lr_0]
pipe_0 = Pipeline().setStages(stages)

# Parameters to test in grid search
# 0: L2/Ridge regularization and 1: L1/Lasso regularization
params = ParamGridBuilder()\
    .addGrid(rForm.formula, ['win_indicator ~ .'])\
    .addGrid(lr_0.elasticNetParam, [0.0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0])\
    .addGrid(lr_0.regParam, [0.1, 2.0])\
    .build()

# Evaluator
evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator()\
    .setMetricName('areaUnderROC')\
    .setRawPredictionCol('prediction')\
    .setLabelCol('win_indicator')
    
cv_0 = CrossValidator(estimator=pipe_0,
                          estimatorParamMaps=params,
                          evaluator=evaluator,
                          numFolds=5)

cvModel_0 = cv_0.fit(train)
In [12]:
# Make predictions on test data.
# Predictions come from the best performing model based on AOC
predTest_0 = cvModel_0.transform(test)\
                .select('win_indicator', 'prediction', 'probability')
    
matrix_0, true_p_0, false_n_0 = get_confusionMatrix(predTest_0)

Random Forest¶

The predictive power of logistic regression proved limited, so a random forest was chosen to investigate whether the results could be improved upon.

The random forest model implemented the same features with the same pipeline of indexing, encoding, and standardizing.

Grid seach and five fold cross validation to find optimal values for maxDepth, maxBins, impurity, and number of trees. Here too the evaluator used area under the ROC to choose the best model.

In [15]:
rf = RandomForestClassifier().setLabelCol('win_indicator').setFeaturesCol('all_features')

stages = indexers+encoders+[s_va, scalers, va, rf]
pipeline = Pipeline().setStages(stages)

# Parameters to test in grid search
params_rf = ParamGridBuilder()\
    .addGrid(rForm.formula, ['label ~ .'])\
    .addGrid(rf.maxDepth, [2, 4, 6])\
    .addGrid(rf.maxBins, [32])\
    .addGrid(rf.impurity, ["entropy", "gini"])\
    .addGrid(rf.numTrees, [5, 15, 20, 30])\
    .build()

# Evaluator
evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator()\
    .setMetricName('areaUnderROC')\
    .setRawPredictionCol('prediction')\
    .setLabelCol('win_indicator')
    
cv_rf = CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline,
                          estimatorParamMaps=params_rf,
                          evaluator=evaluator,
                          numFolds=5)

rf_Model = cv_rf.fit(train)

Clustering and Regression Combined¶

The final model combines k mean clustering with linear regression. In addition to the same categorical features used for th logistic regression and random forest models, the state where the candidate ran was also used. The continuous features remained the same with total contributions and net contributions.

K Means

  • K means was tested with two through six clusters.

Linear regression

  • Linear regression was performed on each cluster produced by the k means model. The same pipeline as above was used to index and create dummy variables for categorical features and scaling for the continuous features.

Grid search and three fold cross validation were used to find optimal values for regParam and elastic net. The evaluator chose the best model based on mean absolute error.

In [25]:
def test_kmeans(n_clusters):
    
    # Convert categorical columns to numeric and create dummy variables
    categorical_columns = ['incumbent_challenger_status', 'party_affiliation', 'candidate_state', 'body']
    indexers = [
        StringIndexer(inputCol=c, outputCol='{0}_indexed'.format(c))
        for c in categorical_columns
    ]

    encoders = [OneHotEncoder(dropLast=True, inputCol=indexer.getOutputCol(),
                            outputCol='{0}_encoded'.format(indexer.getOutputCol()))
                for indexer in indexers
    ]

    scaled_features = ['total_receipts', 'net_receipts']
    s_va = VectorAssembler(
        inputCols=scaled_features,
        outputCol='unscaled_features')

    scalers = StandardScaler(withMean=True, withStd=True,
                             inputCol='unscaled_features', outputCol='scaled_features')

    va = VectorAssembler(
        inputCols=[encoder.getOutputCol() for encoder in encoders]+['scaled_features'],
        outputCol='features')

    km = KMeans(maxIter=50).setK(n_clusters)

    stages = indexers+encoders+[s_va, scalers, va, km]
    pipeline = Pipeline().setStages(stages)
    
    return pipeline
In [26]:
counter = 0
all_results = [['Number of Clusters', 'Cluster Sizes', 'Train MAE', 'Test MAE', 'R2 Values']]
for i in range(2,7):
    
    cluster = test_kmeans(i)
    
    cluster_model = cluster.fit(model_df)
    cluster_prediction = cluster_model.transform(model_df)
    
    summary = cluster_model.stages[-1].summary
    cluster_sizes = summary.clusterSizes
    cluster_weights = [*map(lambda x: x/sum(cluster_sizes), cluster_sizes)]
    
    model_mae_train = 0
    model_mae_test = 0
    r2_values = []
    row = []
    for n in range(0, i):
        
        try:
            labels = cluster_prediction.filter(cluster_prediction['prediction'] == n).select('win_indicator', 'features')
            labels = labels.drop('prediction')
            lr_train, lr_test = labels.randomSplit([0.75, 0.25])

            linReg = LinearRegression(featuresCol='features', labelCol='win_indicator', predictionCol='prediction', 
                                     regParam=0.0, elasticNetParam=0.0)

            params = ParamGridBuilder()\
                .addGrid(linReg.regParam, [0.1, 0.01]) \
                .addGrid(linReg.elasticNetParam, [0.0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0])\
                .build()

            evaluator = RegressionEvaluator()\
                .setMetricName('mae')\
                .setPredictionCol('prediction')\
                .setLabelCol('win_indicator')

            crossVal = CrossValidator()\
                .setEstimator(linReg)\
                .setEvaluator(evaluator)\
                .setEstimatorParamMaps(params)\
                .setNumFolds(3)
             
            lr_model = crossVal.fit(lr_train)
            
            # Predict on TRAIN data
            out_train = lr_model.transform(lr_train)\
                .select('prediction', 'win_indicator')\
                .rdd.map(lambda x: (float(x[0]), float(x[1])))

            metrics_train = RegressionMetrics(out_train)
            
            # Predict on TEST data
            out_test = lr_model.transform(lr_test)\
                .select('prediction', 'win_indicator')\
                .rdd.map(lambda x: (float(x[0]), float(x[1])))

            metrics_test = RegressionMetrics(out_test)
        
        
            train_mae = metrics_train.meanAbsoluteError
            test_mae = metrics_test.meanAbsoluteError
            test_r2 = metrics_test.r2
            
            model_mae_train += cluster_weights[n]*train_mae
            model_mae_test += cluster_weights[n]*test_mae
            r2_values.append(test_r2)
            
        except:
            pass
    
    row = [i] + [cluster_sizes] + [model_mae_train] + [model_mae_test] + [r2_values]
    
    all_results.append(row)

CONCLUSION¶

Money and incumbency both appear to play a role in determining winning candidates, though the relationship is not clear enough to consistently predict winners. Expanding the variables used may improve the accuracy of the model. Possible ways to improve the model could include:

  • separately modeling races by office (i.e. senate, house, and president)
  • adding variables such as age and sex
  • including number of years served for incumbents
  • veteran status
